---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  pageTitle="See rough thinking become review-ready"
  seoTitle="WordPresto workflow demo — rough notes to review-ready content"
  description="A writer's rough notes move through WordPresto. Brief, structure, voice, review and approval — without handing judgement to a machine."
  canonical="https://wordpresto.com/workflow-demo/"
  noindex={true}
>

  <!-- ===================== MASTHEAD ===================== -->
  <header class="masthead">
    <div class="masthead-inner">
      <nav class="masthead-nav masthead-nav--left">
        <a href="/waitlist" class="nav-link">Sign in</a>
        <a href="/#product" class="nav-link">Product</a>
        <a href="/workers/" class="nav-link">Workers</a>
      </nav>
      <a href="/" class="masthead-logo">
        <img src="/brand/main-logo.png" alt="Word Presto — the content engine behind publishing" height="110" />
      </a>
      <nav class="masthead-nav masthead-nav--right">
        <a href="/#use-cases" class="nav-link">Use cases</a>
        <a href="/workers/" class="nav-link">Workers</a>
        <a href="/waitlist" class="btn btn--primary btn--sm">Join the waitlist</a>
      </nav>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ===================== INTRO ===================== -->
  <section class="section section--intro">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="eyebrow eyebrow--demo">Workflow demo</div>
      <h1 class="demo-h1">See rough thinking become review-ready.</h1>
      <p class="demo-intro">A writer's rough notes move through WordPresto. Brief, structure, voice, review and approval — without handing judgement to a machine.</p>
      <p class="demo-note">Follow the steps below. Each one reveals a stage of the content workflow. Nothing is published at the end — human approval is required first.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===================== DEMO AREA ===================== -->
  <section class="section section--demo section--border-top">
    <div class="container">

      <!-- Progress rail -->
      <div class="progress-rail" aria-label="Workflow progress" role="progressbar" aria-valuemin={0} aria-valuemax={9} aria-valuenow={0}>
        <div class="progress-rail-inner">
          {Array.from({ length: 10 }, (_, i) => (
            <span class={`progress-dot${i === 0 ? ' progress-dot--active' : ''}`} data-step={i} aria-label={`Step ${i}`}></span>
          ))}
        </div>
        <span class="progress-label mono-label">Step <span id="progress-current">0</span> of 9</span>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 0: Writer Primer ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step demo-step--visible" id="step-0" data-step="0">
        <div class="step-label mono-label">YOUR NOTES · CLINIC WEBSITE ARTICLE · IN PROGRESS</div>
        <div class="primer-card">
          <div class="primer-margin"></div>
          <div class="primer-body">

            <p class="primer-line primer-line--lead">Why aesthetic clinic websites often fail after launch — even when the design looks polished.</p>
            <p class="primer-line">I want to write about why the website often fails not because the design is wrong, but because the clinic workflow behind it is undefined. The design can look professional and still lose every enquiry because nobody has decided what happens when the message comes in, who it goes to, what a suitable lead actually looks like, or what the patient is supposed to do after they land on the page.</p>
            <p class="primer-line">I don't want this to sound like I'm attacking designers. Good design matters. The point is that design cannot fix an undefined workflow — and that's the clinic's job to sort out first, not the agency's.</p>

            <div class="primer-divider"></div>

            <p class="primer-line primer-line--keep">Keep the phrase: "the website is not the workflow."</p>
            <span class="hand-annot hand-annot--keep">keep this ↓</span>
            <p class="primer-line primer-line--keep">Possibly also: "a form is not a follow-up system."</p>
            <p class="primer-line">The first phrase is the core idea. The second might be the best single line in the whole piece. Not sure whether to use both or just one — writer decision, not the brief's.</p>

            <div class="primer-divider"></div>

            <p class="primer-line">Pain points I want to cover (from real patterns, not invented):</p>
            <p class="primer-line">— WhatsApp enquiries that arrive with no owner — they sit on the clinic manager's phone, sometimes for days, with no handover system<br />
            — Contact forms that collect vague enquiries but no qualification data: no treatment type, no timeline, no sense of whether this is the right patient<br />
            — People booking consultations before anyone has checked suitability — wasted appointments, disappointed patients, staff time lost<br />
            — Staff replying to enquiries in completely different tones depending on who is on shift<br />
            — Clinic owners asking agencies for a better website when the actual problem is the intake process<br />
            — Consent starting at the wrong point — often after the booking, sometimes after the treatment begins<br />
            — Aftercare and follow-up living in a separate system with no connection back to the original enquiry<br />
            — Clinic owners diagnosing a conversion problem when they actually have a workflow problem</p>

            <div class="primer-divider"></div>

            <p class="primer-line">Audience: clinic owners, clinic managers, and possibly agencies who build clinic sites. The tone should be fair to agencies. An agency cannot design around a workflow the clinic hasn't defined. That's the clinic's responsibility first.</p>
            <p class="primer-line">Tone: experienced, fair, practical. Not a lecture. Not another "here is what a great website looks like" piece. No "unlock your digital potential" energy. Domain knowledge, not generic content-marketing voice.</p>

            <div class="primer-divider"></div>

            <p class="primer-line">Claims caution: do not say "most clinic websites fail" without defining what failure means. Failure here means the site does not create a clear, qualified next step for the right kind of patient. Use scenarios rather than statistics.</p>
            <p class="primer-line">Consent and aftercare references should stay operational. Do not stray into legal or compliance advice — that is not this piece.</p>

            <div class="primer-divider"></div>

            <p class="primer-line">Format question — I am not sure what this should become:<br />
            1. An article (probably first)<br />
            2. A landing page section for a service offering<br />
            3. A guide for clinic owners to work through before briefing a website project<br /><br />
            Start as an article. It could feed a service page later. Decision deferred until first draft is shaped.</p>

          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="1">Shape this thinking →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 1: Omar ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-1" data-step="1">
        <div class="worker-pill mono-label">STEP 1 OF 9 · OMAR · CONTENT ANALYST · STAGE: ANALYSE</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Reading your notes. Extracting what matters before a brief is written.</p>
        <div class="output-card">
          <div class="output-card-header">
            <span class="output-card-title">CONTENT ANALYSIS</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body">
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Core argument</div>
              <p class="output-para">The clinic website fails not because the design is wrong, but because the workflow behind it was never defined. Design cannot fix an undefined operational process. That is the clinic's responsibility — not the agency's.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Audience groups identified</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— Primary: clinic owners commissioning or reviewing a website<br />— Secondary: clinic managers who handle day-to-day enquiries<br />— Adjacent: agencies who build clinic sites (this audience changes the tone requirement)<br /><span class="output-indent">→ Writer's note explicitly asks that agencies not be blamed. Brief must carry this.</span></p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section output-section--signal">
              <div class="output-heading output-heading--signal">Two phrases to preserve — both flagged by writer</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— "the website is not the workflow" — core thesis, use as section anchor<br />— "a form is not a follow-up system" — strongest single line in notes; writer uncertain whether to use both<br /><span class="output-indent">Recommendation: keep both. They do different things. First is the argument; second is the best example of it.</span></p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Tension to manage</div>
              <p class="output-para">Writer wants to be fair to agencies. The risk is that the piece reads as "agencies make nice pages and miss the point." That reading alienates a legitimate audience and misattributes blame. The brief should make explicit: the clinic is responsible for defining the workflow before briefing a designer. The agency cannot design around what the clinic hasn't defined.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Likely content format</div>
              <p class="output-para">Writer has deferred the format decision and is starting with an article. This is the right call. The material is strong enough for an article that could later feed a service page or a pre-project guide for clinic owners. Brief as article; note the format optionality for later.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Claims risk areas</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— "Most clinics don't have a system" — unquantified. Use scenarios, not statistics.<br />— Consent and aftercare references must stay operational. No legal framing.<br />— Avoid "most agencies" language — see tension note above.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Missing writer input</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— No specific clinic scenario yet (writer has the WhatsApp pattern; needs one concrete scene)<br />— Conclusion shape is open — writer needs to decide between action list and "what good looks like" example<br />— Word count not yet fixed — brief builder to recommend based on scope</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section output-section--signal">
              <div class="output-heading output-heading--signal">Recommendation</div>
              <p class="output-para">Strong foundation. Two phrases preserved. Format deferred correctly. Proceed to brief — with agency-fairness and claims caution carried through.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="voice-note">
            <span class="hand-note">Two phrases, not one. Both should reach the brief.</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="2">Follow the workflow →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 2: Luca ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-2" data-step="2">
        <div class="worker-pill mono-label">STEP 2 OF 9 · LUCA · CONTENT BRIEF BUILDER · STAGE: BRIEF</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Turning your thinking into a brief that keeps what matters and gives the draft a clear shape.</p>
        <div class="output-card output-card--brief">
          <span class="folder-tab">BRIEF</span>
          <div class="output-card-header output-card-header--ruled">
            <span class="output-card-title">CONTENT BRIEF</span>
            <span class="mono-label">01 · BRIEF · clinic-website-article</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body">
            <dl class="brief-dl">
              <dt class="brief-dt">GOAL</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Help clinic owners see the operational gap that exists before a designer is briefed — and understand that fixing it is their job, not the agency's</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">PRIMARY AUDIENCE</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Clinic owners commissioning or reviewing a website</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">SECONDARY AUDIENCE</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Clinic managers and agencies who build aesthetic clinic sites — tone must be fair to agencies throughout</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">INTENT</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Useful, practical — not a sales piece. No "unlock your digital potential" energy.</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">TONE</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Practitioner-to-practitioner. Direct, warm, slightly wry. Not a lecture.</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">FORMAT</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">Article (first). May feed a service page or pre-project guide later — decision deferred</dd>
              <dt class="brief-dt">WORD COUNT</dt>
              <dd class="brief-dd">900–1,200</dd>
            </dl>
            <div class="brief-divider"></div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">PRESERVE — BOTH PHRASES (writer's instruction)</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— "the website is not the workflow" — section anchor, not the headline<br />— "a form is not a follow-up system" — strongest single example; use to close the forms section<br /><span class="output-indent">Do not paraphrase either. Both are to appear in the draft as written.</span></p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">KEEP</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— Specific clinic scenarios (WhatsApp enquiry pattern, unqualified booking, consent timing)<br />— Operational language throughout — not conversion, not digital strategy<br />— Conversational, not expert-to-layperson</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">AVOID</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— "Most agencies" generalisations — the brief explicitly protects agency readers<br />— "Most clinics fail" — unquantified. Use scenarios instead<br />— Design criticism for its own sake<br />— Generic "here is what a great website looks like" conclusion<br />— Legal or compliance framing around consent — keep operational only</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">SECTIONS</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">1. The problem that happens before design starts<br />2. What a patient actually does when they arrive at a clinic site<br />3. The operational gaps: WhatsApp, weak forms, unqualified bookings, staff consistency, consent, aftercare<br />4. The website is not the workflow [anchor phrase — §4 title]<br />5. What to sort out before briefing a designer<br />Close: what good operational readiness looks like — a scenario, not a checklist</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">OPEN WRITER DECISIONS</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— §3 WhatsApp scenario: writer to provide specific scene (not generalisation)<br />— Closing example: writer to choose between action steps or "what good looks like" scene<br />— "A form is not a follow-up system" placement: writer to confirm — recommendation is end of forms section</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="voice-note">
            <span class="hand-note">Both phrases in the brief. Agency fairness explicit. Format held open correctly.</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="3">Follow the workflow →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 3: Marcus ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-3" data-step="3">
        <div class="worker-pill mono-label">STEP 3 OF 9 · MARCUS · STRUCTURE WORKER · STAGE: STRUCTURE</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Shaping a clear structure that places both phrases where they land hardest.</p>
        <div class="output-card">
          <div class="output-card-header">
            <span class="output-card-title">ARTICLE STRUCTURE</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body output-card-body--outline">
            <div class="outline-row outline-row--h1">
              <span class="outline-tag">H1</span>
              <span class="outline-text">Clinic websites often fail before design starts</span>
            </div>
            <div class="outline-row">
              <span class="outline-tag outline-tag--muted">INTRO</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text">The problem is not the design</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">Open with the WhatsApp scenario — specific, not a generalisation. Draw the reader in before naming the argument.</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="outline-row outline-row--section">
              <span class="outline-tag">§ 1</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text">What a patient actually does when they find the clinic</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">— They don't fill in a form. They send a message.<br />— What happens next depends entirely on whether the clinic has a system.<br />— Most don't. (Use scenario — not a statistic.)</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="outline-row outline-row--section">
              <span class="outline-tag">§ 2</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text">What the enquiry process actually looks like</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">— Qualification: treatment type, timeline, suitability<br />— Staff tone: inconsistent, shift-dependent<br />— Unqualified consultations: wasted appointments, staff time lost<br />— Note on agency role: the brief rarely includes the workflow. That's the clinic's job first.</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="outline-row outline-row--section">
              <span class="outline-tag">§ 3</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text">Where it breaks: forms, consent and aftercare</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">— Contact form collects a name and email. No qualification.<br />— Consent begins after booking — sometimes after treatment.<br />— Aftercare lives in a separate system, disconnected from the original enquiry.<br />— Phrase placement: "A form is not a follow-up system." [close §3]</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="outline-row outline-row--section outline-row--anchor">
              <span class="outline-tag">§ 4</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text outline-text--preserved">The website is not the workflow</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">First phrase as section title and anchor. Named argument. Not the headline — here, mid-article, where it lands after the evidence.</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="outline-row outline-row--section">
              <span class="outline-tag">§ 5</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text">What to sort out before you brief a designer</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">— Operational steps, not a feature list<br />— Framed as: what the designer will need from you that you cannot outsource<br />— Agency fairness protected throughout — the brief defines the constraint</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="outline-row outline-row--close">
              <span class="outline-tag outline-tag--muted">CLOSE</span>
              <div class="outline-content">
                <span class="outline-text">What good looks like — a scenario, not a checklist</span>
                <span class="outline-sub">A clinic that worked through the workflow first. What the agency was able to build as a result. Writer to provide from real experience or composite — not invented.</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="voice-note">
            <span class="hand-note">First phrase: §4 section title. Second phrase: §3 close. Both placed deliberately.</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="4">Follow the workflow →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 4: Helena ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-4" data-step="4">
        <div class="worker-pill mono-label">STEP 4 OF 9 · HELENA · VOICE &amp; STYLE WORKER · STAGE: VOICE</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Reading your notes for register and voice. Checking what must not get edited out.</p>
        <div class="output-card">
          <div class="output-card-header">
            <span class="output-card-title">VOICE &amp; STYLE GUIDANCE</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body">
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Voice identified from your notes</div>
              <p class="output-para">Practitioner-to-practitioner. The reader is not being taught from scratch — they are being reminded of something they probably already half-know. Direct without being blunt. Slightly wry. Domain knowledge, not generic content-marketing voice. The writer's phrase "no unlock your digital potential energy" is instructive — keep that sensibility throughout.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section output-section--signal">
              <div class="output-heading output-heading--signal">Both phrases preserved — exact wording, confirmed positions</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— "the website is not the workflow" — §4 section title and anchor<br />— "a form is not a follow-up system" — §3 close<br /><span class="output-indent">Neither phrase should be paraphrased, softened, or repositioned without writer sign-off.</span></p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">Tone guidance for the draft</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— Open with the specific WhatsApp scenario — a scene, not a statement<br />— The WhatsApp enquiry that sits on someone's phone for two days is a better opening than any abstract claim<br />— Avoid "most clinics" — use "in this pattern" or describe a specific scenario<br />— Agency framing: "The brief rarely includes the workflow" is the right phrasing — observation, not verdict<br />— Consent and aftercare: operational language only. No "legally required" or "compliance" framing.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section">
              <div class="output-heading">What to protect in the draft</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— The register in your notes is experienced and fair, not instructional<br />— The agency-fairness note ("their job is limited to what the clinic has defined") must come through naturally<br />— Conclusion: a scenario, not a list. The piece should end on something the reader can picture, not a bullet list of actions.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="output-section output-section--warning">
              <div class="output-heading output-heading--warning">Risk areas for the drafter</div>
              <p class="output-para output-list">— Do not flatten the voice into generic content-marketing<br />— Do not let agency-fairness become an apology or a hedge — it's a structural point, not a disclaimer<br />— §3 needs one real scenario, not a list of patterns — the list is in the notes; the draft needs the scene</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="voice-note">
            <span class="hand-note">"This sounds like the writer" — do not flatten it into a content template</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="5">Follow the workflow →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 5: Ellis ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-5" data-step="5">
        <div class="worker-pill mono-label">STEP 5 OF 9 · ELLIS · DRAFT REWRITE WORKER · STAGE: DRAFT</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Shaping the opening and early sections. Both phrases in position. Writer gaps held open.</p>
        <div class="output-card output-card--draft">
          <div class="output-card-header">
            <span class="output-card-title">DRAFT EXCERPT · INTRO + §1 + §2 (PARTIAL)</span>
            <span class="status-badge status-badge--review">Draft</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body output-card-body--draft">
            <div class="draft-margin"></div>
            <p class="draft-text draft-text--heading">Clinic websites often fail before design starts</p>
            <p class="draft-text">A WhatsApp arrives on Tuesday afternoon. A prospective patient — she has found the clinic through Instagram, she has a question about a treatment, she thinks the pricing might work. Nobody picks it up until Thursday. By then she has booked somewhere else.</p>
            <p class="draft-text">The clinic has a professional-looking website. Good photography. Clean layout. It did not save the lead.</p>
            <p class="draft-text">The problem was not the website. It was the absence of any system behind it.</p>
            <p class="draft-text draft-text--subheading">§1 · What a patient actually does</p>
            <p class="draft-text">When a patient finds a clinic online, they rarely fill in a contact form. They send a message. Sometimes WhatsApp, sometimes Instagram DM, sometimes a reply to a story. Where that message goes — and what happens to it — depends entirely on whether the clinic has a process for it.</p>
            <p class="draft-text">In many cases, there is no process. The message arrives in someone's inbox. It sits there. The lead is lost not because the clinic is uninterested, but because nobody decided what "handling an enquiry" actually means.</p>
            <p class="draft-text draft-text--subheading">§2 · The brief rarely includes the workflow</p>
            <p class="draft-text">When a clinic commissions a website, the brief tends to cover the things a designer can see: pages, layout, photography, copy. What it rarely covers is what happens when the website works — when someone clicks, enquires, and expects a response.</p>
            <p class="draft-text">That is not the agency's oversight. An agency cannot design around a workflow the clinic has not yet defined. Deciding who handles enquiries, what qualification looks like, and when a consultation is appropriate — those are operational questions. They belong to the clinic, before any brief goes out.</p>
            <p class="draft-text draft-text--subheading">§3 · [WRITER INPUT NEEDED — specific scene for forms and consent gap]</p>
            <p class="draft-text draft-text--anchor-placeholder">[Forms section close] A form is not a follow-up system.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="voice-note">
            <span class="hand-note">Both phrases drafted in. §3 scene held open for you — that part is yours.</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="step-cta-wrap">
          <button class="demo-cta" data-reveals="6">Follow the workflow →</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== STEP 6: Quinn ===== -->
      <div class="demo-step" id="step-6" data-step="6">
        <div class="worker-pill mono-label">STEP 6 OF 9 · QUINN · DRAFT QUALITY REVIEWER · STAGE: REVIEW</div>
        <p class="worker-action">Checking the draft against the brief. What is working. What still needs the writer.</p>
        <div class="output-card">
          <div class="output-card-header">
            <span class="output-card-title">DRAFT QUALITY REVIEW</span>
          </div>
          <div class="output-card-body output-card-body--checklist">
            <div class="review-row review-row--pass">
              <span class="review-icon review-icon--pass">✓</span>
              <div class="review-text">
                <span class="review-item">Opening scene (WhatsApp, Tuesday)</span>
                <span class="review-note">— specific, grounded, earns attention without claiming anything</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="review-row review-row--pass">
              <span class="review-icon review-icon--pass">✓</span>
              <div class="review-text">
                <span class="review-item">Agency-fairness framing</span>
                <span class="review-note">— "An agency cannot design around a workflow the clinic has not yet defined" — exactly right</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="review-row review-row--pass">
              <span class="review-icon review-icon--pass">✓</span>
              <div class="review-text">
                <span class="review-item">"The website is not the workflow" — §4 anchor</span>
                <span class="review-note">— positioned correctly; arrives after evidence, not before</span>
              </div>
